abstract: Tariffs slapped by China on U.S. products cost the most affected communities billions of dollars in lost auto sales in 2018 as the hit to local incomes undercut household spending, according to an analysis released on Wednesday by the National Bureau of Economic Research.
snippet: Tariffs slapped by China on U.S. products cost the most affected communities billions of dollars in lost auto sales in 2018 as the hit to local incomes undercut household spending, according to an analysis released on Wednesday by the National Bur...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Tariffs slapped by China on U.S. products cost the most affected communities billions of dollars in lost auto sales in 2018 as the hit to local incomes undercut household spending, according to an analysis released on Wednesday by the National Bureau of Economic Research.
headline_main: China Retaliatory Tariffs Cost Billions in Lost Consumption: Study
headline_print_headline: China Retaliatory Tariffs Cost Billions in Lost Consumption: Study

abstract: Trump’s trade adviser invokes his anti-China alter ego to influence the trade debate.
snippet: Trump’s trade adviser invokes his anti-China alter ego to influence the trade debate.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A critical decision about China tariffs is looming, and Ron Vara, Peter Navarro’s hawkish alter ego, has re-emerged to share some thoughts on the matter.

abstract: The British prime minister is more grim tactician now than “the clownish, cuddly fellow” of the past. So far, it seems to be working.
snippet: The British prime minister is more grim tactician now than “the clownish, cuddly fellow” of the past. So far, it seems to be working.
lead_paragraph: UTTOXETER, England — On the second-to-last day of Britain’s landmark election campaign, Prime Minister Boris Johnson drove a backhoe through a wall of Styrofoam bricks. The wall was labeled “Gridlock,” while the backhoe was emblazoned with a Union Jack and the slogan “Get Brexit Done.”

abstract: Mexico's Foreign Minister Marcelo Ebrard said Wednesday that U.S. President Donald Trump could designate Mexican drug gangs as terrorist groups whenever he chooses, but this designation would be negative for bilateral cooperation.
snippet: Mexico's Foreign Minister Marcelo Ebrard said Wednesday that U.S. President Donald Trump could designate Mexican drug gangs as terrorist groups whenever he chooses, but this designation would be negative for bilateral cooperation.
lead_paragraph: MEXICO CITY — Mexico's Foreign Minister Marcelo Ebrard said Wednesday that U.S. President Donald Trump could designate Mexican drug gangs as terrorist groups whenever he chooses, but this designation would be negative for bilateral cooperation.
headline_main: Trump Could Still Label Cartels as Terrorists, but U.S.-Mexico Relations Would Suffer: Mexican Official
